  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/63930169?book_show_action=true">Jul 17, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephanie Ricker" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephanie Ricker" href="/user/show/1361805-stephanie-ricker">Stephanie Ricker</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1361805-stephanie-ricker?shelf=horses">horses</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer63930169" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8902550572191550920">Chosen by a Horse was a sodden, sentimental, dreary, shallow thing which somehow became a bestseller. Then again, I suppose those adjectives could be applied to many bestsellers. Ugh. My coworkers are very sweet and often lend me books. Sometimes, they&apos;re fantastic. Other times...less so. Yet I always feel compelled to read them all the way through! Why, why??</span>
